<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1881-03-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1881-03-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="231" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d231">
                    <head>No. 227.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Noyes</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Blaine</persName></hi>.</head>
                    <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1881-03-21"><hi rend="italic">March</hi> 21,
                            1881</date>.</dateline></opener>
                    <p>President Grévy informally accepts invitation to Yorktown celebration, and
                        says that as France shared in the danger and cost of securing <pb facs="0529" n="405" xml:id="pg_405"/> national independence to America,
                        she gladly takes part in rejoicing over the victory.</p>
                    <closer><signed>NOYES.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>